A generic in programming (especially in Java) allows you to write classes, interfaces, and methods that can operate on different data types without losing type safety.

Example:

ArrayList<Integer> nums = new ArrayList<>();
ArrayList<String> words = new ArrayList<>();


ArrayList is defined using a generic type <T>, meaning it can store any type you specify at compile time.
Benefits of generics:

Type safety (prevents storing the wrong type)

No need for type casting

Reusable code that works with multiple types

In short: Generics let you create flexible, reusable code that remains strictly typed.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

2. In which situation/set-up is recursion best avoided?

Recursion should generally be avoided when:

The problem requires very deep or large recursive calls

Risk of stack overflow if the recursion goes too deep.

A simple iterative solution exists

Loops are often faster and more memory-efficient.

Performance and efficiency are critical

Recursive calls add overhead due to repeated function calls.

Example of where recursion is NOT ideal:

factorial(50000)  // will likely overflow stack


In these cases, an iterative approach is safer and more efficient.
