3. When would we prefer throw/throws over try/catch?

We use throw/throws instead of try/catch when:

We donâ€™t want to handle the exception in the current method

We want to let the calling method decide how to handle the error

We want to propagate the exception up the stack

Example:

public void readFile() throws IOException {
    FileReader file = new FileReader("data.txt");  // may throw error
}
